</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The first spacewalk is to be done by Steven Smith, a veteran of
two previous flights, including the 1997 mission to work on Hubble,
and John Grunsfeld, also a veteran of two missions. The team plans
to replace three Rate Sensor Units, each of which contains two of
the crucial gyroscopes. It also plans to install
voltage/temperature improvement kits to protect Hubble's six
batteries from overcharging and overheating when the observatory is
in safe mode and not using much power.
</P>
<P>
   C. Michael Foale, a veteran of five shuttle flights and of a
four-month stay on the Russian space station, Mir, in 1997, and
Claude Nicollier, a European Space Agency astronaut who flew on the
first Hubble service mission in 1993 and on two other shuttle
flights, expect to conduct the second walk. This team plans to
replace the telescope's central computer with one that is 20 times
as fast and has six times as much memory. The astronauts also
expect to swap one of Hubble's three Fine Guidance Sensors for an
improved version that should enhance the observatory's pointing and
measurement capability.
</P>
<P>
   Smith and Grunsfeld are scheduled for the third walk during
which they are to replace a radio transmitter and swap a tape
recorder that stores data on reels for a faster, solid-state model
that stores information on computer chips. The astronauts also are
to upgrade other electronics and begin reinforcing the telescope's
thermal covering.
</P>
<P>
   On the fourth spacewalk, Foale and Nicollier plan to do more
work on Hubble's outer insulation and coverings, found during the
1997 mission to be damaged and deteriorating because of exposure to
sunlight and to small amounts of atomic oxygen. The astronauts are
to attach stainless steel sheets covered with a thermal coating
over existing insulation on Hubble's exterior surface.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Ham, the flight director for the mission at the Johnson
Space Center, said the effort would be considered a success if the
crew completed all the tasks of the first two spacewalks, including
leaving a complete set of working gyroscopes. The work of the last
two spacewalks would be a bonus, Ms. Ham said, and would relieve
the workload on the next service flight.
</P>
<P>
   NASA officials said the mission would cost about $205 million.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Leckrone, senior project scientist for Hubble, said
the telescope should be back in action within three weeks to a
month after the mission. ``We can't wait to get it back online,''
he said.
</P>
